GROWTH SECTOR

Healthcare is a growth sector in a low growth world
Healthcare is a long-term, secular growth sector as an older population drives the demand and the need for increased healthcare provision. Global healthcare spending was over $7.6 trillion in 2014 and is projected to grow faster than GDP. The political conundrum is how to deliver better healthcare to more people for less money. Healthcare companies with products or services that deliver demonstrable value and drive efficiency are well-placed for growth.


Click to view the video 


Click to view the video 


Click to view the video 


Click to view the video 


Click to view the video 









HEALTHCARE DISRUPTED

Structural change creates new investment opportunities
Greater efficiency is the catalyst for information technology to finally disrupt 20th century healthcare systems. Technology is transforming the way that healthcare is managed, delivered and paid for and so changing the competitive structure of the industry. This shifting landscape creates investment opportunities that extend well beyond the familiar pharmaceutical companies.


Click to view the video 


Click to view the video 


Click to view the video 


Click to view the video 


Click to view the video 









EXPERT KNOWLEDGE

Experienced team with a track record
Polar Capital’s Healthcare team is highly experienced with a broad and diversified skill-set and a strong track record. They anticipated the investment opportunity of an out-of-favour pharmaceutical sector in 2010 with the original launch of PCGH. As healthcare specialists, they combine expert knowledge with an investment process based on fundamental research, active stock-picking and careful risk management.


Click to view the video 


Click to view the video 


Click to view the video 


Click to view the video 


Click to view the video 









IDENTIFYING WINNERS

Two-pronged investment strategy to profit from structural change
The team believes successful companies can be divided into two categories. The consolidators – large companies that recognise and adapt to change resulting in stable earnings and cash flow growth and compounding investment returns. The innovators – smaller companies with new products, services or business models that drive disruption.


