In 1995, Karen Shirk was told she was too disabled to receive a service dog. She decided to make sure no one else ever had to hear those words.
4 Paws for Ability is the embodiment of Karen’s vision - a nonprofit organization that breeds, socializes, trains, and places service dogs with children and veterans. Since its inception in 1998, 4 Paws has paired over 1,100 trained service dogs to people living with a variety of disabilities. With a team of 75 employees and over 600 volunteers, 4 Paws now places over 100 dogs per year. 4 Paws dogs (and the humans they love and serve) can be found in almost all 50 statesas well as Australia, Canada, Germany, Japan, Mexico, New Zealand, and Switzerland. 


Our first priority is always to reunite our youth with healthy, functional family. For the majority of our kids for whom family is not an option, we give them an educational & vocational assessment and help them find a job that suits their skills and interest. We offer many services to help, from mock interviews & resume writing classes to workshops on basic life skills and healthy relationships.





Dogs trained through 4 Paws meet the criteria for ‘service animals’ as defined by the Americans
with Disabilities Act (ADA). These dogs serve in diverse areas:
• Diabetic alert
• Seizure alert
• Hearing assistance
• Autism assistance
• Mobility assistance
• Multipurpose assistance
• PTSD assistance
• Assistance for children with Fetal Alcohol
• Syndrome Disorder (FASD)/drug exposure


















The 4 Paws journey begins with an in-house breeding program that produces healthy dogs with the behavioral profile needed to succeed as an assistance animal. The dogs are accustomed to human interaction from their first day of life; staff and volunteers assist in the whelping rooms and continuously monitor the new litters. As soon as the puppies are weaned, they are moved to the Puppy House. This is a popular volunteer opportunity; imagine walking into a house full of puppies, spending hours playing and cuddling with them!
Puppies soon begin public socialization. This is a critical time in a puppy’s development. Puppies, under careful supervision, are slowly exposed to various stimuli - crowds, grass, leashes, service dog vests - to acclimate them to life as a service dog. They are then moved out of the puppy house and into the care of a puppy raiser.
Some of our dogs enter a traditional foster home setting, with volunteers who commit not only to the raising of a puppy that is not their own, but also to the challenging (and rewarding) task of exposing that puppy to the widest possible number of socialization opportunities. Other dogs spend time at one of four Ohio correctional facilities we use for four-six weeks learning basic obedience, potty training, and crate training by vetted inmates who attend a weekly class with a 4 Paws trainer.




Other puppies join the 4 Paws University program. Currently, 4 Paws partners with 25 universities within a three-hour radius of the facility; student organizations are established on these campuses to foster several dogs at a time, often in teams that allow for greater diversity in the puppies’ experiences. College campuses provide an enormous variety of socialization opportunities, from classroom environments (important for those dogs who will serve a school-aged child) to sporting events. Many of our 4 Paws dogs have walked with their college fosters across the stage as the students receive their diplomas; the students love the chance to share this important achievement with their foster pup, who helped make their college experience so memorable and rewarding.
Around one year of age, the professional training staff at 4 Paws evaluate each dog to determine if the dog meets the strict criteria necessary to continue in advanced training. Some dogs are not selected for advanced training; at this point, they are made available for adoption. The 4 Paws team likes to call these dogs the ‘fabulous flunkies’ - loving dogs who fell just short of the narrow standards needed for service doghood. Many happy dog owners have found their perfect companion - and many happy dogs have found ‘forever homes’ - through the adoption program. 
The dogs who continue in the advanced training program begin rigorous instruction with the training staff. It is here the dog is trained for the specific task that will serve their ‘match’ - the child or veteran who has been on their own journey while their service dog in training has been working so hard. 


















The dog, you see, is only half the team.
While the dog has been learning everything from ‘sit’ to ‘leave it’ to the intricate training required to alert a potential medical crisis, the recipient of the dog has been busy. Service dogs are not covered by most insurance plans, and a fully trained service dog through 4 Paws costs between $40,000-$60,000. Families who have been approved by 4 Paws are asked to pay or fundraise $17,000 (except veterans who are completely free); 4 Paws provides promotional assistance and training during the fundraising process. Most families have multiple events during their fundraising period. Some families raise the required amount; others find they raise enough money to cover the full cost of the dog. Excess funds are administered through 4 Paws to families who may have fallen short during the fundraising process, adhering to one of the most fundamental principles of the 4 Paws mission: no one approved through the 4 Paws application process is denied because of the inability to pay.
The final steps of the journey are made together by the child or veteran with disabilities and the service dog who has been trained as their companion. The final two weeks of training show the recipient how to work with (and begin life with) a new service dog. During this time, the bonding process begins - the start of a lifetime partnership between human and canine.
A graduation ceremony at the end of the training allows the puppy raisers and the new service dog families to celebrate the successful completion of the training process, connecting individuals who were impacted by the raising and training of these dogs.





http://www.4pawsforability.org/























Covenant House New Orleans was founded on the edge of the French Quarter 30 years ago to provide a safe haven for homeless, runaway, and at-risk youth (ages 22 and under). We have provided over 20,000 kids with food, shelter, clothing, medical care, educational and vocational support, individual and family counseling, job readiness and placement, short & long-term housing, life skills, and more.
The vast majority of our youth have endured physical and/or sexual abuse and have also experienced the violence of the streets. Our counselors estimate 85% suffer from some form of traumatic stress disorder. Tulane’s Cowen Institute estimates there are 26,000 at-risk youth in our community. Our first priority is always to reunite our youth with healthy, functional family. For the majority of our kids for whom family is not an option, we give them an educational & vocational assessment and help them find a job that suits their skills and interest.


http://www.covenanthouseno.org

















Soldiers’ Angels provides aid and comfort to the men and women of the United States Army, Marines, Navy, Air Force, Coast Guard, and their families and a growing veteran population. Soldiers’ Angels was established in 2003 by the mother of a son who was deployed to Iraq. She began sending care packages to her son and was then asked to not only send more care packages to many more deployed but to also assist with other needs. September 11th was a catalyst that inspired Americans to support the military and help out any way they could. Soldiers’ Angels was created as an opportunity for them to provide that support with care packages, hand-sewn blankets, letters, cards, and other items from ‘home’.
In just 14 years, since this small beginning of sending care packages, Soldiers’ Angels has grown to over 12 Programs with over 100,000 volunteers nationwide. Most of the programs and services offered by Soldiers’ Angels are performed by volunteers who work tirelessly supporting our nation’s veterans, wounded warriors, deployed service members and their families.


http://www.soldiersangels.org




















On May 12th, HPFY donated 10% of the day’s sales to ‘Asha for Education’. Asha for Education took roots in 1991 when a group of students including Deepak Gupta, Sandeep Pandey, and VJP Srivatsavoy from the University of Berkeley, CA got together and discussed ways to bring about a socio-economic change in India. The group was formed with a belief that education is a requisite to bring about the much needed socio economic change in India. It was named ‘Asha’, meaning ‘hope’. Since then, Asha for Education has grown via its chapters, and today has more than 65 chapters worldwide.
 Asha for Education is a 501(c)(3) organization in the US. Each year, our work touches the lives of several thousands of children across a few hundreds of projects. We have no offices, and 100% of our efforts are driven by unpaid volunteers. All donations are tax deductible, and we have earned a reputation for sending >98% of donations to our projects.


http://www.ashanet.org























On April 14th, HPFY donated 10% of the day’s sales to ‘Doug Fluite, Jr. Foundation for Autism’. The Flutie Foundation awards grants to individuals and families dealing with the challenges of autism.
The Doug Flutie, Jr. Foundation for Autism, Inc. was established in 1998 by former NFL quarterback Doug Flutie and his wife, Laurie, in honor of their son, Doug, Jr. who was diagnosed with autism at the age of three. Through their General Grants, Joeys Fund, Allison Keller Technology fund and other programs and initiatives, The Flutie Foundation awards grants to individuals and families dealing with the challenges of autism as well as to the organizations that support them. The grants that they provide give individuals with autism access to much needed educational and other support services, autism specific active lifestyles programs and assistance with transitioning to adult independence. In addition The Flutie Foundation, through their grant programs, awards grants to nonprofit organizations that provide direct services such as family support, education, advocacy and recreational opportunities for individuals with autism.


http://www.flutiefoundation.org
























On March 10th, two days after International Women’s day, HPFY donated 10% of the day’s sales to Women’s of Danbury.
Since 1975, the Women’s Center of Greater Danbury has been a safe haven as the sole provider of services to victims of domestic and sexual violence in the Northern Fairfield and Southern Litchfield County areas. Each year the Center serves over 25,000 individuals from our area communities. Our FREE and confidential services are available 24 hours a day, 7 days a week, 365 days a year. The Center’s key areas of focus include emergency shelter and support services, counseling and advocacy, crisis intervention, and community education, primary prevention and training.
All funds provided to the Center support our critically needed domestic violence, sexual assault, and resource services for adults and children in our 13-town service area, including: Bethel, Bridgewater, Brookfield, Danbury, Kent, New Fairfield, New Milford, Newtown, Redding, Ridgefield, Roxbury, Sherman and Washington.


http://www.wcogd.org
















